            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Ontario tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your combined
                <strong>Ontario provincial</strong> and
                <strong>federal</strong> income tax, plus
                <strong>CPP</strong> and <strong>EI</strong> payroll deductions,
                based on the latest published brackets and rates for the
                selected tax year.
              </p>
              <p>
                It is designed for <strong>Ontario residents</strong> with
                employment and/or self‑employment income. It assumes standard
                situations and does not handle every special rule (e.g., complex
                business deductions, stock options, or multi‑province
                residency).
              </p>

              <h3>1. Taxable income</h3>
              <p>Your taxable income is calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code>
                  taxable income = employment income + self‑employment income −
                  RRSP contributions − other deductions
                </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                RRSP contributions and other deductible amounts reduce your
                taxable income, which lowers both federal and provincial tax.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Federal tax brackets (example 2025)</h3>
              <p>For 2025, the federal brackets (approximate) are:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>15% on the first $55,867 of taxable income</li>
                <li>20.5% on the portion over $55,867 up to $111,733</li>
                <li>26% on the portion over $111,733 up to $173,205</li>
                <li>29% on the portion over $173,205 up to $246,752</li>
                <li>33% on the portion over $246,752</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator applies these marginal rates to your taxable
                income, then subtracts the
                <strong>basic personal amount</strong> and any extra
                non‑refundable credits you specify.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Ontario provincial tax brackets (example 2025)</h3>
              <p>Ontario’s provincial brackets (approximate) are:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>5.05% on the first $51,446</li>
                <li>9.15% on the portion over $51,446 up to $102,894</li>
                <li>11.16% on the portion over $102,894 up to $150,000</li>
                <li>12.16% on the portion over $150,000 up to $220,000</li>
                <li>13.16% on the portion over $220,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                As with federal tax, the Ontario basic personal amount and your
                additional credits reduce the actual tax payable.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Ontario surtax</h3>
              <p>
                Ontario applies a <strong>surtax</strong> on higher provincial
                tax amounts (before credits). The calculator approximates this
                using:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>20% surtax on Ontario tax over the first threshold</li>
                <li>
                  Additional 36% surtax on Ontario tax over the second threshold
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This effectively increases the marginal rate at higher incomes.
                The surtax is included in the
                <strong>Ontario surtax</strong> line in the breakdown.
              </p>

              <h3>5. CPP and EI contributions</h3>
              <p>
                If you leave CPP and EI enabled, the calculator estimates
                mandatory contributions on your
                <strong>employment income</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>CPP</strong>: a percentage of pensionable earnings
                  between the yearly basic exemption and the maximum.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>EI</strong>: a percentage of insurable earnings up to
                  the annual maximum.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Self‑employment income is not subject to EI, and CPP on
                self‑employment is more complex; for simplicity, this tool
                focuses on CPP/EI for T4 employment income.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Effective tax rate</h3>
              <p>The <strong>effective tax rate</strong> is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <code> effective rate = total income tax ÷ total income </code>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is lower than your top marginal rate because the first
                dollars you earn are taxed at lower brackets.
              </p>

              <h2>Example: $75,000 salary in Ontario</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you earn $75,000 in employment income, with no RRSP
                contributions and standard credits.
              </p>
